WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.360 --> 00:00:04.199
Staff who did the work. And that's Ethan and

2
00:00:04.240 --> 00:00:04.740
Evan.

3
00:00:05.880 --> 00:00:08.690
nice to meet you all. So I'm Ethan McKenzie.

4
00:00:08.780 --> 00:00:10.440
I led this piece of work as audit lead.

5
00:00:12.660 --> 00:00:15.680
Flooding is New Zealand's most frequent natural hazard, and climate change is

6
00:00:15.720 --> 00:00:18.099
projected to increase its frequency and severity.

7
00:00:18.880 --> 00:00:22.280
Our performance audit of Waikato Regional Council and Tasman District Council

8
00:00:22.720 --> 00:00:26.320
looked at how well these councils plan, fund and manage flood

9
00:00:26.380 --> 00:00:29.560
protection infrastructure to mitigate the risk of flooding from lakes, rivers and

10
00:00:29.640 --> 00:00:30.900
other inland bodies of water.

11
00:00:31.940 --> 00:00:35.340
However, this report and its findings is also intended to highlight some good

12
00:00:35.420 --> 00:00:39.340
practice and lessons learned to help all 23 councils responsible for flood

13
00:00:39.380 --> 00:00:41.730
protection to improve how they manage that activity.

14
00:00:42.600 --> 00:00:46.350
To clarify our scope, the flood protection and control works activity, which is

15
00:00:46.360 --> 00:00:49.180
what we looked at for each of these councils, does not include coastal flooding or

16
00:00:49.220 --> 00:00:50.480
coastal erosion mitigation.

17
00:00:51.520 --> 00:00:55.130
So the headline findings from this report are that each council is in slightly

18
00:00:55.140 --> 00:00:58.840
different places when it comes to information they hold about flood protection

19
00:00:58.860 --> 00:01:02.180
infrastructure and how they prioritize and plan work on that

20
00:01:02.220 --> 00:01:02.860
infrastructure.

21
00:01:04.240 --> 00:01:07.730
Waikato Regional Council is in a generally good place on that front, while Tasman

22
00:01:07.760 --> 00:01:10.560
District Council has some more work to do to ensure they have good asset

23
00:01:10.620 --> 00:01:14.180
information and more systematic prioritization and planning.

24
00:01:14.200 --> 00:01:17.120
Happy to answer more questions about that if the committee has any.

25
00:01:17.800 --> 00:01:21.580
We also recommended that both councils improve their understanding of flood risk.

26
00:01:22.100 --> 00:01:24.760
And when we say flood risk, we mean something quite specific.

27
00:01:24.840 --> 00:01:25.220
So,

28
00:01:27.320 --> 00:01:31.140
we saw that they both have a generally good understanding of

29
00:01:31.160 --> 00:01:34.680
where it is likely to flood under different scenarios, so where the water will go

30
00:01:34.740 --> 00:01:36.000
when a flood is likely to occur.

31
00:01:37.440 --> 00:01:40.740
However, they only understand the likely impact of that flooding for some areas in

32
00:01:40.780 --> 00:01:43.970
their region. So that includes the impact on people's lives and

33
00:01:44.020 --> 00:01:47.590
livelihoods, as well as financial, economic, cultural and

34
00:01:47.640 --> 00:01:48.900
environmental impacts.

35
00:01:50.180 --> 00:01:53.860
We understand that that's not unique to these two councils, and

36
00:01:53.920 --> 00:01:56.580
research indicates that risk is not consistently well understood

37
00:01:56.620 --> 00:01:58.200
nationwide.

38
00:01:59.520 --> 00:02:02.220
But this is important because flood protection requires quite significant

39
00:02:02.240 --> 00:02:06.020
investment. Councils need good information about flood risks

40
00:02:06.380 --> 00:02:09.680
and flood protection infrastructure to make well-informed trade-offs between cost

41
00:02:09.700 --> 00:02:10.241
and risk.

42
00:02:11.240 --> 00:02:13.790
And these trade-offs, if informed well, helps them make

43
00:02:14.060 --> 00:02:17.540
sound investment

44
00:02:17.560 --> 00:02:18.160
decisions,

45
00:02:19.060 --> 00:02:20.700
and to protect people and property from flooding.

46
00:02:22.880 --> 00:02:25.620
This is especially important given the cost pressures facing councils.

47
00:02:26.340 --> 00:02:30.280
In particular, in their 2024 to '34 long-term plans, councils are planning

48
00:02:30.290 --> 00:02:31.940
to borrow at historically high levels.

49
00:02:33.280 --> 00:02:34.040
So in conclusion,

50
00:02:35.280 --> 00:02:38.380
to manage flood protection infrastructure to mitigate flood risk effectively,

51
00:02:39.540 --> 00:02:42.620
all councils responsible for flood protection need to, in our view,

52
00:02:43.420 --> 00:02:47.400
firstly, understand the current and future flood risk for a range

53
00:02:47.420 --> 00:02:50.950
of different flooding scenarios in their regions, including the projected impact of

54
00:02:51.020 --> 00:02:51.780
climate change.

55
00:02:53.040 --> 00:02:57.010
Secondly, understand and maintain their flood protection infrastructure, including

56
00:02:57.040 --> 00:03:00.420
understanding the costs involved in achieving different options for intended levels

57
00:03:00.460 --> 00:03:01.080
of service.

58
00:03:02.900 --> 00:03:05.920
Thirdly, they need to inform their communities about flood risk,

59
00:03:06.660 --> 00:03:10.580
intended and actual levels of service and costs, including through regular

60
00:03:10.660 --> 00:03:13.900
proactive communication about the potential impact of flooding now and in the

61
00:03:13.940 --> 00:03:14.340
future.

62
00:03:15.820 --> 00:03:19.460
And fourthly, they need to understand their community's views on where they should

63
00:03:19.500 --> 00:03:22.780
focus their flood protection efforts. So, happy to take questions.

64
00:03:23.160 --> 00:03:24.109
Thank you. And

