00:12:37.108 --> 00:12:40.248
the houses that are actually on a lower-lying area.

254
00:12:40.358 --> 00:12:44.208
And it seems council don't seem to even think about the lay of the

255
00:12:44.308 --> 00:12:46.868
land when they actually permit these kinds of activities.

256
00:12:46.928 --> 00:12:48.648
Are they doing anything about those?

257
00:12:52.548 --> 00:12:53.708
So currently,

258
00:12:55.348 --> 00:12:58.838
under the draft national policy statement for natural hazards, which is currently

259
00:12:58.888 --> 00:12:59.637
being considered,

260
00:13:00.448 --> 00:13:00.758
there is a

261
00:13:01.988 --> 00:13:05.868
suggested requirement in there that councils take into account

262
00:13:05.908 --> 00:13:08.808
natural hazard risk when they're planning new developments.

263
00:13:08.888 --> 00:13:09.398
That

264
00:13:10.588 --> 00:13:12.068
is not the case with the current system.

265
00:13:12.668 --> 00:13:16.637
Councils aren't required to consider risk when they make decisions

266
00:13:16.688 --> 00:13:18.628
about where flood protection infrastructure is going to go.

267
00:13:19.968 --> 00:13:23.218
But that's something that we think that they should consider doing because

268
00:13:23.528 --> 00:13:25.228
you're pointing to

269
00:13:25.668 --> 00:13:29.588
what seems like, to most, common sense

270
00:13:29.628 --> 00:13:33.508
logic, which is if you're going to build flood protection somewhere,

271
00:13:33.788 --> 00:13:35.288
flood protection is extremely expensive.

272
00:13:35.328 --> 00:13:37.548
You want to make sure that you're getting value for money for that spend.

273
00:13:37.588 --> 00:13:40.968
There's no point building an enormous stopbank to protect it

274
00:13:41.428 --> 00:13:43.908
because it's going to drain relatively quickly.

275
00:13:43.928 --> 00:13:47.088
But it might make more sense to build it where there's a new development or

276
00:13:47.988 --> 00:13:50.718
an existing development that seems to be flooding more frequently than it had been

277
00:13:50.748 --> 00:13:51.388
before.

278
00:13:52.428 --> 00:13:52.528
Yeah.

279
00:13:52.538 --> 00:13:52.768
Yeah.

280
00:13:52.868 --> 00:13:55.588
It would make sense to actually not build flood protection

281
00:13:56.388 --> 00:14:00.348
infrastructure when you have better planning system where you're

282
00:14:00.408 --> 00:14:04.388
actually not getting rid of soakage areas, where rain can actually go

283
00:14:04.408 --> 00:14:05.848
around the drain.

284
00:14:06.268 --> 00:14:10.188
Yeah, that's right. So those are challenging decisions

285
00:14:10.228 --> 00:14:13.088
that councils have to make, but there are a lot of different ways that they can

286
00:14:13.108 --> 00:14:16.848
mitigate risk to communities. Building stopbanks and flood pumps,

287
00:14:17.028 --> 00:14:18.808
stuff like that, is one of them.

288
00:14:19.768 --> 00:14:22.708
There are plenty of other things as well, more natural things like restoring

289
00:14:22.728 --> 00:14:25.708
wetlands. There's a range of different things that they could consider.

290
00:14:25.728 --> 00:14:29.188
But in order to decide which of those things to do, they need really good

291
00:14:29.228 --> 00:14:32.227
information, not just about where the water's going, but what's going to happen

292
00:14:32.248 --> 00:14:35.768
when it gets there. And that's the part that we think these two councils need to

293
00:14:35.808 --> 00:14:37.368
improve, and we think all councils should consider.

294
00:14:37.428 --> 00:14:39.628
Okay, we'll move to Mike for the last question.

295
00:14:40.008 --> 00:14:40.308
Thank you.

296
00:14:41.868 --> 00:14:45.528
You mentioned here that obviously councils can face litigation

297
00:14:45.608 --> 00:14:48.758
risk if they don't meet their intended levels of services.

298
00:14:49.328 --> 00:14:53.188
Obviously, councils, through proper process, can reduce

299
00:14:53.208 --> 00:14:56.888
their levels of service to ensure they are meeting it,

300
00:14:57.888 --> 00:15:01.128
which therefore does technically put community at risk.

301
00:15:01.368 --> 00:15:04.378
What protections are in place to stop councils just

302
00:15:04.468 --> 00:15:08.128
reducing their levels of service or having a low level of service that actually

303
00:15:08.228 --> 00:15:11.868
still puts communities at risk?

304
00:15:15.828 --> 00:15:19.628
Essentially, the process for changing levels of service requires

305
00:15:20.208 --> 00:15:22.388
formal consultation and a change to long-term plans.

306
00:15:22.758 --> 00:15:23.808
I'm unaware of any formal

307
00:15:24.828 --> 00:15:28.288
things in place to mitigate that, but I guess they'd have to front up with their

308
00:15:28.368 --> 00:15:31.198
communities and do it in an open and transparent way, and

309
00:15:32.628 --> 00:15:35.808
whether they want to do that, that's a decision that individual councils will make.

310
00:15:35.868 --> 00:15:36.788
But that seems to be

311
00:15:38.028 --> 00:15:38.848
the key thing.

312
00:15:40.448 --> 00:15:42.758
Great. Thank you. And thank you very much for that.

313
00:15:42.828 --> 00:15:44.088
We've come to the end of our time.

314
00:15:44.528 --> 00:15:44.748
Thank you.

